        <h3><i class="mdi-content-send brown-text"></i></h3>
        <h4>“Sometimes you're more likely to get a concussion in the women's game because we don't grow up hitting.” -Caitlin Cahow </h4>
        <p class="light body-text" align="justify">Women’s ice hockey is becoming increasingly dangerous due to the lack of checking within the female side of the sport. While boys grow up learning how to check, women are not granted the same opportunity (unless they choose to participate in boy’s hockey from a young age) to learn the body positioning needed to take the force of a hit (Whiteside). Caitlin Cahow, a women’s Olympic ice hockey player, suffered from a severe concussion and ultimately ended her career in hockey because of her brain injury. Cahow was not able to participate in every day activities without experiencing an immense amount of pain (Whiteside). She was unable to stand outside for periods of time over five minutes because the brightness of the sun was too much to handle. </p>
