          <h3 class="header col s12 light section3-title">A Call To Action</h3>
          <p class="col s12 light section3-text" align="justify" id="action-call-text">USA Hockey needs to make changes to the checking rule within women's ice hockey. While ice hockey is a growing sport for women to play in countless countries, Charlene Weaving and Samuel Roberts claim that women who play ice hockey are not awarded the same opportunities as men to excel within the sport (470). Sports, in general, are implemented into our society in a patriarchal manner. Women are seen as less athletic than men, therefore checking should not be allowed within women's ice hockey. However, the logic behind this claim seems to be absent within the sport of ice hockey. Checking is not allowed within the women's side of the sport even though females are allowed to play alongside men where checking is allowed and yet females in this situation experience concussions at a lower rate than females in women's hockey. Therefore, it can be surmised, that women are not inherently more susceptible to concussions than their male counterparts, but, rather lack of checking in women's hockey results in lower body agency which leads to an increased risk of concussions in this population.</p>
